      <preliminaryRqmts>
        <preliminaryRqmtsDescr>Aircraft powered, hydraulic systems A, B, and C pressurized. CMS maintenance terminal connected. Surface rigging verified within limits (Ref: 27-XX-00-710-801).</preliminaryRqmtsDescr>

        <safety>
          <warning>
            Deactivation of actuator channels during this test can induce rapid surface movement. Ensure all spoilers are pinned and gust locks are engaged.
          </warning>
          <caution>
            Do not cycle deactivated surfaces more than specified cycles to prevent actuator thermal overload or fluid foaming.
          </caution>
          <note>
            CMS will flag actuator channel loss detection; monitor system warnings and fault trees for correct identification of channel failures.
          </note>
        </safety>
      </preliminaryRqmts>

      <mainProcedure>
        <step>
          <para>Access CMS Actuator Override and Fault Simulation page (Ref: 45-00-00-860-801). Select target surface (Aileron, Elevator, or Rudder).</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Manually isolate Hydraulic System A supply to target actuator via CMS override.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Command surface full range motion using CMS. Confirm remaining hydraulic channels (B/C) maintain full authority. Observe CMS actuator feedback for smooth, unchattered movement.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Reactivate System A. Repeat test by isolating Hydraulic System B supply.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Command surface motion again. Confirm System A and C redundancy take over without fault flags beyond 3 sec limit.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>Finally, isolate Hydraulic System C and repeat. Confirm System A and B redundancy full functionality.</para>
        </step>
        <step>
          <para>For each isolation event, verify CMS fault tree logs "Channel X Loss" correctly within 5 seconds. Validate automatic logic recovery where specified.</para>
        </step>
      </mainProcedure>

